            <h1>Introduction to Statistics</h1>
            <h1>Mean, median, and mode</h1>
            <p>
                These properties allow us to put number sets into perspective; to see the middle numbers and the relationship of the central mass of the data to the outliers.
            </p>
            <br>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Mean: The average, sum of all points divided by the number of all points.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Median: The centre of the data set if all points are aligned in order.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Mode: The most frequent/repeating point.
                </li>
            </ul>
            <h2>Mean</h2>
            <p>
                The mean is great for talking about data that is <strong>normally</strong> distributed. meaning that the data is equally spread out on both sides, with the most common values appearing in the middle.
            </p>
            <figure>
                <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/introduction-to-statistics/statsNormalDist.png">
                <figcaption>A typical normal distribution of an arbitrary data set, note the blue line in the centre represents the mean.</figcaption>
            </figure>
            <p class="note">
                <strong>Distribution</strong> shows us how often each value occurs in a data set; otherwise called a frequency.
            </p>
            <h2>Median</h2>
            <p>
                Allows us to reduce the influence of extreme values, outliers, on a data set. It is the central number with data lined up in order. If two numbers are in the central point then we take the man of both to produce the median. The median shows the central number, both sides are as A- and B are equal.
            </p>
            <h1>Introduction: Statistics</h1>
