            <h2>Basic Concepts: Variable</h2>
            <p>
                Each measure is called an <strong>observation</strong>. For one instance we can have multiple measures, thus multiple observations. A <strong>statistical series</strong> is thus an ensemble of observations.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Quantitative Variables:</strong> A variable can be a variety of things. It can be: quantitative, the height of a man, number of accidents. It can either be continous, such as the height of a man, or discontinous such as the number of accidents; which can only be expressed by whole integers.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Qualitative Variables:</strong> It can also be qualitative and thus descriptive. Such as, the colour of vehicules, the sex of a person. Here each possibility is called a modality or a class: <a href="../../../dictionaries/dicFormulas.html#FDic_classModality">Class or Modality</a>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Moreover a quantitative variable can be expressed in qualitative ordinal form by constituting classes d'appartenance"".
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Example:</strong> Consider a population of employees in France. A monthly salary S is the quantitative variable we are measuring. We can thus construct the variable SO which is an ordinal qualitative variable and holds four modalities or classes:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Class 1: S &lt; 10 000
                </li>
                <li>
                    Class 2: 10 000 &lt; S &lt; 20 000
                </li>
                <li>
                    Class 3: 20 000 &lt; S &lt; 30 000
                </li>
                <li>
                    Class 4: S &gt; 40 000
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                <strong>Census:</strong> A study of all individuals from a specific population. This is difficult in practice when dealing with large populations.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Survey:</strong> The gathering of data points from a specific population. The part of this population that is studies is called the <strong>sample</strong>. The gathering of survey data from an initial population is done by statistical techniques called: <strong>Sampling Methods</strong>.
            </p>
