            <h1>Law of Probabilities</h1>
            <p>
                In the laws of probabilities you can have two cases, discrete and continous probabilities.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Discret: Binomial law, Poisson...
                </li>
                <li>
                    Continous: Normal law, Law of Chi2...
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                In discret cases the law of probability noted <span>P(X)</span> is assinged the probability of <span>p(X=u)</span> at each value of u which belongs to an ensemble of possible values taken from the random variable <span>X</span>.
            </p>
            <p>
                In continous cases the law of probability noted <span>P(X)</span> is assinged the probability of <span>P(a &le; X &le; b)</span> within the specific interval <span>[a, b]</span> which in turn belongs to the space <span>X</span>.
            </p>
            <p>
                To put things into stupid so that I can understand it myself a discret law will have its values <span>u</span> equal to one value that comes from the whole of <span>X</span> which can be anything since it is random. But in the case of continous laws, here we have the law of probability which assigns the possibilities to an interval meaning that the answers or results can only fall within a certain interval, and of course this interval belongs to the space of <span>X</span>; so here <span>X</span> is greatly limited.
            </p>
            <p>
                It seems that in the discret case being that <span>X</span> can be random its values have infinite possibilities, thus you limit it by going into the continous case by placing it into an interval.
            </p>
